==================================================================9600 1451   90
  MF/MT combinations used to define ALL electron interaction data 9600 1451   91
  are newly defined MF/MT numbers for ENDF/B-VI that did not exist9600 1451   92
  in earlier versions of ENDF/B.                                  9600 1451   93
==================================================================9600 1451   94
  Definition of Data                                              9600 1451   95
==================================================================9600 1451   96
  Cross Sections (MF=23)                                          9600 1451   97
==================================================================9600 1451   98
1) The total electron interaction cross section is given          9600 1451   99
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/501. It is the sum of scatter,          9600 1451  100
   bremsstrahlung, excitation and ionization cross sections,      9600 1451  101
   i.e., MT = 526, 527, 528, and 534 through 572.                 9600 1451  102
2) The total electron ionization cross section is given           9600 1451  103
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/522. It is the sum of the aubshell      9600 1451  104
   cross sections, i.e., all MT = 534 through 572.                9600 1451  105
==================================================================9600 1451  106
  Angular and Energy Distributions (MF=26)                        9600 1451  107
==================================================================9600 1451  108
3) For Large Angle Scatter (MT=525), angular distributions of     9600 1451  109
   electrons are tabulated between cosine = -1.0 and 0.999999.    9600 1451  110
   Between +0.99999 and +1.0 it is analytically defined as        9600 1451  111
   Coulomb scattering,                                            9600 1451  112
                                                                  9600 1451  113
   d(sig)/d(cos) = A/[eta+(1.0 - cos)]^2                          9600 1451  114
                                                                  9600 1451  115
   where the shielding parameter (eta) is defined by the          9600 1451  116
   Steve Seltzer expression (see, ref. 1), and (A) is the         9600 1451  117
   normalization factor for the integral +0.99999 to +1.0.        9600 1451  118
   Electron elastic scatter means no energy loss, so only         9600 1451  119
   angular distributions are giving.                              9600 1451  120
4) For bremsstrahlung, both the outgoing electron and photon are  9600 1451  121
   described. The photon energy spectra are given, but angular    9600 1451  122
   distributions are not; these can be analytically defined by a  9600 1451  123
   number of different methods. For the electron, average energy  9600 1451  124
   loss is given. The electron is assumed to continue along its   9600 1451  125
   original direction of travel, so angular distributions are not 9600 1451  126
   given. WARNING - bremsstrahlung is a three body process,       9600 1451  127
   involving an electron, a photon, and an atom - so that you     9600 1451  128
   cannot use energy or momentum correlation to simply relate     9600 1451  129
   the secondary electron and the emitted photon.                 9600 1451  130
5) For excitation, the average energy loss of the electron is     9600 1451  131
   given. The electron is assumed to continue along its original  9600 1451  132
   direction of travel, so angular distributions are not given.   9600 1451  133
6) For Ionization, the spectra of electrons is given. The electron9600 1451  134
   is assumed to continue along its original direction of travel, 9600 1451  135
   so angular distributions are not given. In ionization two      9600 1451  136
   identical electrons emerge; the incident electron, and an      9600 1451  137
   electron ejected by the atom [thereby ionizing the atom]. Since9600 1451  138
   the two particles are indistinquishable, we define the electron9600 1451  139
   with the lower energy to be that ejected by the atom, and the  9600 1451  140
   electron with the higher energy to be the incident electron.   9600 1451  141
   The energy of the two electrons is exactly correlated by energy9600 1451  142
   conservation: initial incident electron energy = binding energy9600 1451  143
   of the ejected electron, plus the kinetic energy of the ejected9600 1451  144
   and the secondary incident electron. Therefore only the spectra9600 1451  145
   of the lower energy, ejected electron is given. The energy of  9600 1451  146
   the secondary incident electron should be defined to conserve  9600 1451  147
   energy, as described above. The energy lost by the incident    9600 1451  148
   electron is the sum of the binding and kinetic energy of the   9600 1451  149
   ejected electron.                                              9600 1451  150
7) Relaxation of ionized atoms back to neutrality is not described9600 1451  151
   here; it is described in the companion Evaluated Atomic Data   9600 1451  152
   Library (EADL).                                                9600 1451  153
